collection.description: This collection features our conversations throughout the State of Maine held with educators, students, community members, and major Maine industry professionals. We are asking what youth will need to thrive personally, civically, and economically in the Maine of 2050. The collection is expanding daily, so check back!
collection.title: Maine ED 2050

highlights.description: Student lives are not as good, often, as ours lives were when we were young
Same as before - hard home life
High numbers of substance abuse in homes.
This was a big point in our convo, discussing SEL
Students need to be "adults" without the maturity/skill set.

I am noting the relationship between my response and the one below from Hilary. Elaborating on my response: Some kids have much more than their peers and they may or may not know this. They also may not appreciate it. Other students do not have what others have and 9-10 years old is an age where kids start noticing this more and it changes their view of the world, perhaps causing anger, anxiety, resentment, etc.
Conversations from students coming from substance abuse homes, nasty divorces, poverty, lack of hope, and lack of education.
Students are more open-minded than adults
Students need guidance/mentoring/coaching on how they can overcome the life they do not want...
Changing graduation requirements (state and local) to match the changes in the culture/time?
Kids may begin to not like school when they begin to develop their OWN selves and we treat them all the same, same schedule, same assignments, etc
Even my 10-year-old students are taking care of younger siblings in the middle of the night and in the morning, so they come to school, tired, stressed, and disheveled.
The lack of family structure is an ongoing theme.

I want to highlight this because I've had SO any conversations with parents, former students, teachers, who can vouch this is time when REAL connections and relationships were made and it is NO longer... makes me very sad

I thought about this more after our conversation. I wonder if they struggle working independently because they have not had as much practice doing so under teacher facilitation and guidance and did so more alone at home with worksheets or alone on a laptop when they learned virtually. Perhaps because of this, they like working together more.
Same- we need to build relationships to build test scores...

I am unsure if Covid and learning at home in their younger years contributed to the struggle with growth mindset and positive attitude of self. Do we teach this right away as they are young and because they did not get that when 1st and 2nd grade, that is why we are seeing more of this struggle. Or is it because of Covid and lack of in-person teaching at a young age that they have less love or school and that struggle with growth mindset.

I agree this set of high school students can be more resilient as adults due to what they have faced as children.  It will depend on the influences that either help lead them to help them succeed or succumb to what they have grown up in.
ACES scores are soooo important to understand and they should impact our curriculum and how we teach
Big lack of school / parent connections right now, I think we need specific plans to improve upon this
I agree with Hillary on this fact.  The earlier we are able to start building students' skills the better.

Our intention with this grant was for students to get BOTH guidance and extra SEL from teachers because we saw the need. A couple years later, when needed most, we eliminated guidance in the schools as a special. We hired more Social workers, which is great, but all kids could benefit from the guidance courses.
